    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Slender climbing plant with twining hairy stems and narrow, arrow-shaped, opposite velvety leaves that curl under at the sides. The striking tubular flowers are bright pink or red and have long pointed petals with green tips that close the mouth of the tube. Flowers are borne in heads of about 5-8 flowers each. The forked fruit split open along the seam when ripe to release distinctive brown seeds each topped by long, silky hairs.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9640",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Grows to at least 1 m, supported by other plants. Leaves about 30 mm long. Flowers up to about 11 mm tall.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9641",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namaqualand to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9642",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found in the winter-rainfall regions, where it clambers into other shrubs. Plants are heavily grazed by stock and game and the young fruits are a popular wild food with a milky-sweet taste. The flowers are also sometimes eaten.</p><p>Makes an attractive pot or garden plant but difficult to grow from seeds, which survive best if sown just before the winter rains.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9643",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9644",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flower June-September. Pollinated by sunbirds that penetrate the closed flowers, resulting in the pollen sacs attaching to the birds’ tongues – a unique and specialized form of bird pollination. Butterflies and ants also visit the flowers for their sweet nectar. The parachute-like hairs on the seeds assist with wind dispersal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9645",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Distinctive growth form and flowers. The closely-related Coral creeper or Redwax creeper <i>M. tenuifoloum</i> has much the same range and habits, but has narrow thread-like leaves and urn-shaped, open-ended bright-red flowers with rounded petals.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9646",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
